Problem Statement

Context

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist at EasyVisa have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

Summary

Actionable Recommendations

Based on the insights derived from model performance and feature importance, EasyVisa can provide the following strategic recommendations to both the OFLC and employers:

For OFLC (Facilitating Visa Approvals & Streamlining the Process)

Automated Pre-screening

  • Implement the ML model for initial shortlisting
    Use the trained XGBoost model to pre-screen applications and flag those with high probability of certification. This reduces manual workload for straightforward approvals and allows focus on complex or borderline cases.

  • Prioritize review based on model scores
    Fast-track applications with high predicted certification probability. Applications with high predicted denial probability can be flagged for secondary review or automated rejection.

Data-Driven Policy Refinement

  • Review "Requires Job Training" feature
    This feature had very low importance in the model. OFLC may consider reducing emphasis on it in the manual process or streamline how it's collected.

  • Analyze regional and continental patterns
    Investigate why continent and region_of_employment are influential. This may uncover regional labor shortages or nationality-specific patterns that inform policy development.

Feedback Loop for Model Improvement

  • Regular model retraining
    Retrain the model quarterly or annually to reflect up-to-date immigration trends and labor market dynamics.

  • Human-in-the-loop validation
    Maintain a human review process for borderline predictions to continuously evaluate and improve model accuracy and fairness.

For Employers (Optimizing Applicant Profiles for Higher Approval Chances)

Focus on Highly Qualified Candidates

  • Prioritize education and experience
    Applicants with Masters or Doctorate degrees and relevant work experience show higher certification probability.

  • Clearly highlight job experience
    Ensure job experience is well-documented and relevant to the position being applied for.

Competitive Wage Offers

  • Meet or exceed prevailing wage
    Offering wages above the prevailing rate increases approval chances and ensures INA compliance.

  • Use consistent wage units
    Where possible, use yearly wage units (unit_of_wage_Year) to improve clarity and avoid misinterpretation.

Strategic Employment Planning

  • Prefer full-time positions
    Full-time roles (full_time_position_Y) have higher approval likelihood than part-time roles.

  • Consider regional demand
    Certain U.S. regions (e.g., Midwest, South) show higher approval trends. Align hiring strategies with regional demand patterns.

Documentation and Clarity

  • Submit comprehensive applications
    Ensure all relevant employee detailseducation, experience, and wageare accurate and complete.

  • Minimize job training needs (if possible)
    While not critical, reducing the need for extensive training may improve the perceived readiness of the candidate.

Next Steps for EasyVisa

  • Deployment strategy
    Plan integration of the model into OFLC systems for seamless operation.

  • User interface development
    Build a clean and user-friendly interface for OFLC staff to input data and receive predictions with explanations (e.g., feature importance highlights).

  • Bias detection and mitigation
    Analyze model predictions across continents and regions to detect and correct any potential biases.

  • Scenario analysis for employers
    Build tools to simulate how changes in applicant features (e.g., wage, education level) affect approval probability.

  • Long-term monitoring
    Set up a monitoring framework to track model drift, maintain accuracy, and ensure fairness over time.

# function to create labeled barplots
def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot stacked bar chart
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 6))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

### function to plot distributions wrt target


def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Step 1: Define bins from 0 to 10,000 with step 1,000, plus an extra bin for >10,000
bins = list(range(0, 11_000, 1000)) + [np.inf]  # Adds an extra bin for >10,000
labels = [f'{bins[i]}-{int(bins[i+1])}' if bins[i+1] != np.inf else '10000+' for i in range(len(bins)-1)]

# Step 2: Bin the data
df['employee_bin'] = pd.cut(df['no_of_employees'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False)

# Step 3: Create pivot table
bin_counts = df.pivot_table(index='employee_bin', columns='case_status', aggfunc='size', fill_value=0)

# Step 4: Add row-wise totals
bin_counts['Total'] = bin_counts.sum(axis=1)

# Step 5: Add column-wise totals
total_row = pd.DataFrame(bin_counts.sum(axis=0)).T
total_row.index = ['Total']
bin_counts = pd.concat([bin_counts, total_row])

# Display final result
print(bin_counts)

# 1. Remove invalid values: zero or negative employee counts
df = df[df['no_of_employees'] > 0].copy()

# 3. Log-transform the employee count (good for skewed features)
df['log_employees'] = np.log1p(df['no_of_employees_capped'])  # log(1 + x)

# 4. Bin employee counts into interpretable categorical ranges
bins = list(range(0, 11_000, 1000)) + [25_000, 50_000, 100_000, np.inf]
labels = [
    '01k', '1k2k', '2k3k', '3k4k', '4k5k', '5k6k', '6k7k', '7k8k', '8k9k', '9k10k',
    '10k25k', '25k50k', '50k100k', '100k+'
]
df['employee_bin'] = pd.cut(df['no_of_employees_capped'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False)

Model evaluation criterion

Model can make wrong predictions as:

  1. Model predicts that the visa application will get certified but in reality, the visa application should get denied.
  2. Model predicts that the visa application will not get certified but in reality, the visa application should get certified.

Which case is more important?

  • Both the cases are important as:

  • If a visa is certified when it had to be denied a wrong employee will get the job position while US citizens will miss the opportunity to work on that position.

  • If a visa is denied when it had to be certified the U.S. will lose a suitable human resource that can contribute to the economy.

How to reduce the losses?

  • F1 Score can be used a the metric for evaluation of the model, greater the F1 score higher are the chances of minimizing False Negatives and False Positives.
  • We will use balanced class weights so that model focuses equally on both classes.

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Model Building - Original Data

Intro to KFold Cross Validation:

  1. Definition:
  • K-Fold Cross-Validation is a resampling technique used to evaluate the performance of a machine learning model. It splits the dataset into K subsets (folds), trains the model on K-1 folds, and tests it on the remaining fold. This process is repeated K times, with each fold used as the test set exactly once. The final performance is the average of the evaluation metric (e.g., accuracy, recall, etc.) across all folds.
  1. Why We Use K-Fold Cross-Validation:
  • Robust Performance Estimation: It provides a better estimate of a models performance by using all data points for both training and testing (but not at the same time).
  • Reduces Overfitting: Unlike a single train-test split, K-Fold Cross-Validation ensures the model is tested on multiple unseen subsets of data, reducing the chance of overfitting to a specific dataset split.
  • Maximizes Data Usage: It uses all data for training and testing at different stages, making it ideal for small datasets where splitting once may not be sufficient.
  1. Analogy 1:

  • Context: Imagine you're preparing for a big exam. Instead of solving one full-length practice test, you divide the syllabus into K topics. Each time, you study K-1 topics and take a mini-test on the remaining topic. You repeat this process until you've tested yourself on every topic. Finally, you average your scores across all tests to determine how well-prepared you are.

  • K topics = K folds.

  • Studying K-1 topics = Training the model on K-1 folds.

  • Testing on the remaining topic = Testing the model on the remaining fold.

  • By the end of this process, you have a clear idea of your strengths and weaknesses across the entire syllabus, just like K-Fold Cross-Validation gives a clear picture of the model's performance across the dataset.

  1. Analogy 2:

  • Context: Sports Team Practice. Imagine you're coaching a sports team, and you want to prepare them for a big game. Instead of having everyone practice together all the time, you divide the team into K groups and follow this process:

  • You let K-1 groups practice together (this is your training phase).

  • The remaining group plays a practice match against the others to test their skills (this is your testing phase).

  • Rotate the groups, so each group gets a chance to be the test group once.

  • By the end, every group has been tested, and you've identified strengths and weaknesses across the entire team.

  1. Key Takeaways:
  • K-Fold Cross-Validation ensures the model is rigorously tested on all parts of the data.
  • It prevents biased evaluations and increases confidence in a model's ability to generalize.

Model Building - Oversampled Data

Oversampling in Machine Learning

Definition

Oversampling is a technique used in machine learning to address class imbalance in classification problems. It involves increasing the number of instances in the minority class by duplicating existing samples or generating synthetic samples, so that both classes are better represented in the dataset.

Why We Use Oversampling

In imbalanced datasets, machine learning models tend to be biased toward the majority class. This can lead to poor performance when predicting the minority class, especially in metrics like recall, precision, or F1-score. Oversampling helps correct this bias.

What It Is Used For

  • Binary classification problems with a significant class imbalance (e.g., fraud detection, disease diagnosis)
  • Multiclass problems where one or more classes are underrepresented
  • When improving the model's ability to detect rare events is more important than overall accuracy

How Its Helpful

  • Improves model generalization to the minority class
  • Increases recall and F1-score for minority classes
  • Reduces the likelihood that the model will ignore rare but important classes
  • Helps in training stable models with more balanced decision boundaries

Common Oversampling Techniques

  • Random Oversampling: Simply duplicates random samples from the minority class.
  • SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique): Generates new, synthetic examples by interpolating between existing minority class instances.
  • ADASYN: An extension of SMOTE that focuses on difficult-to-learn examples.

What Is SMOTE?

SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) is one of the most widely used oversampling methods. Instead of duplicating existing samples, SMOTE creates new synthetic data points by selecting a sample from the minority class and introducing new samples along the line segments joining that sample and its k-nearest minority class neighbors. This process increases the diversity of the minority class and helps the model learn a more general decision boundary. SMOTE is especially useful because it avoids the risk of overfitting that often occurs with simple duplication, and it helps balance the dataset in a more realistic way by enriching the feature space with new, interpolated examples.

How Are Synthetic Samples Not Fake?

Synthetic samples are not "fake" in the sense of being random or unrelated to the actual data. Instead, they are systematically generated from real data points using mathematical interpolation. For example, SMOTE creates new points by calculating values that lie between existing minority class samples in the feature space. These new samples preserve the structure, distribution, and relationships present in the real data, allowing the model to learn patterns more effectively. While synthetic, they are grounded in actual data and represent plausible variations that the model could encounter in the real world.

from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

# 1. Define your oversampling technique:
sm = SMOTE(
    sampling_strategy=1,     # Balance the classes so that minority and majority have equal numbers (1:1 ratio)
    k_neighbors=5,           # For each minority sample, SMOTE selects 5 nearest neighbors from the same class
    random_state=1           # Seed for reproducibility
)  # Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique

# Apply SMOTE to the training data only (never apply to validation or test sets)
X_train_over, y_train_over = sm.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# What is k_neighbors=5?
# For each minority class instance, SMOTE finds its 5 nearest neighbors using Euclidean distance.
# Then, it randomly selects one of those 5 neighbors and creates a synthetic sample along the line
# connecting the original point and the neighbor. This process is repeated until the desired class
# balance is achieved. k_neighbors=5 is the default and a common choice to ensure diversity in synthetic samples.

Model Building - Undersampled Data

Undersampling in Machine Learning

Definition

Undersampling is a technique used to handle class imbalance in machine learning by reducing the number of samples in the majority class. This is done to create a more balanced dataset, which can help the model learn to recognize patterns in both classes more fairly.

Why We Use Undersampling

In highly imbalanced datasets, models tend to favor the majority class, often misclassifying minority class examples. Undersampling reduces this bias by balancing the class distribution, allowing the model to pay more attention to the minority class. Its particularly useful when the dataset is large and computational efficiency is a concern.

What It Is Used For

  • Binary classification problems where the majority class overwhelms the minority class (e.g., spam detection, credit default)
  • When we have a large dataset and want to reduce training time
  • When preserving all majority class data is not critical, and some loss of information is acceptable

How Its Helpful

  • Helps the model focus equally on both classes
  • Reduces training time and computational cost by trimming the dataset size
  • Improves recall and precision for the minority class in some cases
  • Avoids overfitting to the majority class

Common Undersampling Techniques

  • Random Undersampling: Randomly removes samples from the majority class.
  • Tomek Links: Identifies and removes borderline majority class instances that are close to minority class examples.
  • NearMiss: Selects majority class samples that are closest to minority class instances, keeping only the most informative ones.

What Is RandomUnderSampler?

RandomUnderSampler is a basic and widely used undersampling technique provided by libraries such as imbalanced-learn. It works by randomly selecting a subset of the majority class so that it matches the size of the minority class. This straightforward approach is efficient and easy to apply, especially when the dataset is large and can afford to lose some examples. Although it may discard potentially useful data, RandomUnderSampler is useful when training speed is important or when models are severely overfitting due to class imbalance. It is often used as a baseline before trying more advanced undersampling techniques.

How Is Reduced Data Still Useful?

Even though undersampling removes some data, the remaining majority class samples are often sufficient for the model to learn general patterns, especially when the dataset is initially large. The key idea is that reducing quantity does not necessarily mean losing qualitythe algorithm still sees enough diversity in the majority class to build accurate decision boundaries. Additionally, careful selection techniques like NearMiss ensure that only the most informative samples are retained, making the reduced dataset both smaller and more efficient for learning.

Hyperparameter Tuning

### GridSearchCV vs. RandomizedSearchCV

Criteria GridSearchCV RandomizedSearchCV
Search Method Exhaustive search over specified parameter values. Random search over a specified parameter distribution.
Parameter Space Evaluates all possible combinations of parameters. Evaluates a fixed number of random parameter combinations.
Execution Time Generally longer due to exhaustive search, especially with large parameter spaces. Generally shorter because it evaluates fewer combinations.
Computational Cost Higher, because it evaluates all combinations. Lower, because it evaluates a subset of combinations.
Likelihood of Finding Optimal Parameters Higher if the parameter space is small, because all combinations are tested. Depends on the number of iterations and the randomness of sampling; good for large parameter spaces.
Use Case Suitability Best for small to medium-sized parameter grids where exhaustive search is feasible. Best for large parameter grids where exhaustive search is impractical.
Control Over Search Full control over the parameter combinations to be tested. Less control; relies on random sampling.
Scalability Less scalable with an increasing number of parameters or parameter values. More scalable with an increasing number of parameters or parameter values.
Implementation Simplicity Simple but potentially requires more computing resources. More complex but can be more efficient in terms of resource usage.
Parallel Processing Supports parallel processing to speed up the search. Supports parallel processing to speed up the search.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations

Model Performance (XGBoost Classifier on Test Set)

Metric Score
Accuracy 0.751
Recall 0.889
Precision 0.773
F1 Score 0.827

  • Accuracy: 0.751 (75.1%) - This indicates that the model correctly predicts the case status (Certified/Denied) for about 75% of the applications. While decent, there's room for improvement.

  • Recall: 0.889 (88.9%) - This is a strong recall score. It means that out of all the actual 'Certified' cases, the model correctly identified 88.9% of them. This is crucial for the OFLC's objective of facilitating visa approvals, as it minimizes the chances of denying a deserving applicant.

  • Precision: 0.773 (77.3% - This means that when the model predicts a 'Certified' case, it is correct 77.3% of the time. There's a balance to strike here; while we want high recall, we also want to minimize false positives (predicting 'Certified' when it should be 'Denied').

  • F1 Score: 0.827 (82.7%) - The F1 score is a harmonic mean of precision and recall, providing a good overall measure of the model's accuracy, especially when dealing with imbalanced classes (which is often the case in certification/denial scenarios). An F1 score of 0.827

Top features influencing visa approval:

  • education_of_employee_High School, Master's, Doctorate
  • has_job_experience_Y
  • log_wage, unit_of_wage_Year, prevailing_wage
  • region_of_employment_Midwest, South, Northeast
  • continent_Europe, North America
  • Full-Time Position (Y)
  • Requires Job Training (Y)
  • Number of Employees / Year of Establishment

  • Education of Employee (High School, Master's, Doctorate): This is by far the most significant driver. "Education of employee_High School" having the highest importance suggests that the level of education plays a crucial role, potentially indicating that applicants with higher education levels (Master's, Doctorate) are more likely to be certified, while those with only high school education might face more scrutiny or be less frequently certified.

  • Has Job Experience (Y): Having previous job experience is the second most important factor, indicating that experienced candidates are preferred or have a higher likelihood of approval.

  • Log Wage / Prevailing Wage: The "log wage" (likely a transformed version of prevailing wage) and "prevailing_wage" itself are important, suggesting that the proposed wage relative to the prevailing wage in the area is a significant consideration. This aligns with the INA's goal of protecting US workers' wages.

  • Unit of Wage (Year): The unit in which the wage is reported (e.g., yearly being more impactful than weekly or hourly) also influences the outcome.

  • Continent of Employee / Region of Employment: The continent of origin and the intended region of employment in the US are also moderately important, suggesting potential regional demand or historical approval patterns.

  • Full-Time Position (Y): Whether the position is full-time or part-time is a relevant factor.

  • Requires Job Training (Y): This feature has very low importance, suggesting that whether an employee requires job training has minimal impact on the visa approval decision.

  • Number of Employees / Year of Establishment: These employer-related features (especially no_of_employees_capped, employee_bin_X-Yk, company_age, yr_of_estab) have relatively low importance compared to employee-specific attributes.

Actionable Recommendations

Based on the insights derived from model performance and feature importance, EasyVisa can provide the following strategic recommendations to both the OFLC and employers:

For OFLC (Facilitating Visa Approvals & Streamlining the Process)

Automated Pre-screening

  • Implement the ML model for initial shortlisting
    Use the trained XGBoost model to pre-screen applications and flag those with high probability of certification. This reduces manual workload for straightforward approvals and allows focus on complex or borderline cases.

  • Prioritize review based on model scores
    Fast-track applications with high predicted certification probability. Applications with high predicted denial probability can be flagged for secondary review or automated rejection.

Data-Driven Policy Refinement

  • Review "Requires Job Training" feature
    This feature had very low importance in the model. OFLC may consider reducing emphasis on it in the manual process or streamline how it's collected.

  • Analyze regional and continental patterns
    Investigate why continent and region_of_employment are influential. This may uncover regional labor shortages or nationality-specific patterns that inform policy development.

Feedback Loop for Model Improvement

  • Regular model retraining
    Retrain the model quarterly or annually to reflect up-to-date immigration trends and labor market dynamics.

  • Human-in-the-loop validation
    Maintain a human review process for borderline predictions to continuously evaluate and improve model accuracy and fairness.

For Employers (Optimizing Applicant Profiles for Higher Approval Chances)

Focus on Highly Qualified Candidates

  • Prioritize education and experience
    Applicants with Masters or Doctorate degrees and relevant work experience show higher certification probability.

  • Clearly highlight job experience
    Ensure job experience is well-documented and relevant to the position being applied for.

Competitive Wage Offers

  • Meet or exceed prevailing wage
    Offering wages above the prevailing rate increases approval chances and ensures INA compliance.

  • Use consistent wage units
    Where possible, use yearly wage units (unit_of_wage_Year) to improve clarity and avoid misinterpretation.

Strategic Employment Planning

  • Prefer full-time positions
    Full-time roles (full_time_position_Y) have higher approval likelihood than part-time roles.

  • Consider regional demand
    Certain U.S. regions (e.g., Midwest, South) show higher approval trends. Align hiring strategies with regional demand patterns.

Documentation and Clarity

  • Submit comprehensive applications
    Ensure all relevant employee detailseducation, experience, and wageare accurate and complete.

  • Minimize job training needs (if possible)
    While not critical, reducing the need for extensive training may improve the perceived readiness of the candidate.

Next Steps for EasyVisa

  • Deployment strategy
    Plan integration of the model into OFLC systems for seamless operation.

  • User interface development
    Build a clean and user-friendly interface for OFLC staff to input data and receive predictions with explanations (e.g., feature importance highlights).

  • Bias detection and mitigation
    Analyze model predictions across continents and regions to detect and correct any potential biases.

  • Scenario analysis for employers
    Build tools to simulate how changes in applicant features (e.g., wage, education level) affect approval probability.

  • Long-term monitoring
    Set up a monitoring framework to track model drift, maintain accuracy, and ensure fairness over time.
